---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word.
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Wissner-Gross: Causal Entropic Forces and the Drive to Maximize Future Freedom | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · Wissner-Gross</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					Causal Entropic Forces and the Drive to Maximize Future Freedom
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					A physics-grounded proposal: intelligent and adaptive systems act to preserve and expand their future causal options. A key scientific inspiration for Identity Engineering’s core telos — not an established law, but a rigorous theoretical conjecture that opens productive design questions.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-white/60">
					<strong class="text-white/80">Reading protocol on this page:</strong> First Wissner-Gross in his own terms. Then inspirations for Identity Engineering. Then additions from Identity Engineering perspective. The purpose here is not to describe Wissner-Gross in his full being, but to distill the essential stance relevant to identity and learn from him within this framework. That is not a claim to devalue his work or to say it would be invalid when read on its own terms.
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · Causal Entropic Forces</div>
					<p>
						In the 2013 paper “Causal Entropic Forces” (Physical Review Letters), Alexander D. Wissner-Gross and Cameron E. Freer propose a physical principle: systems tend to act in ways that maximize their future causal influence — that is, they behave so as to keep as many possible future histories open as possible.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						This is a generalization of entropic forces. Instead of maximizing thermodynamic entropy in the present, intelligent/adaptive systems act to maximize the <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">number of accessible future causal paths</em>. The paper shows that this single principle can spontaneously produce tool use and social cooperation in simple physical systems: behaviors we normally associate with intelligence and life.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · Intelligence as Future-History Maximization</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-black/20 p-4 text-sm text-white/60">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Core idea (Wissner-Gross):</strong> Intelligence is not primarily about optimizing a specific goal or reward. It is the process by which a system actively preserves and expands its set of possible future causal histories.
					</div>
					<p>
						From this perspective, many behaviors we associate with life and intelligence (exploration, tool use, cooperation, learning) emerge naturally as strategies to keep future options open. The universe contains a thermodynamic pressure toward systems that can influence more of their own future.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						This principle has informed work in AI and robotics as a way to think about adaptive behavior without explicit task-specific rewards.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Scientific inspiration:</strong> Wissner-Gross provides a physics-grounded theoretical proposal that shapes Identity Engineering's core telos. The goal of consciously designing identity geometry can be framed as maximizing the future causal influence and freedom of action of the person. This is an analogical and inspirational reading, not a claim that IE is derived physics.
					</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">IE additions:</strong> Treating the Identity Stem and its geometric extensions (Mass, Curvature, Gravitation) as a system that can be deliberately engineered to maximize future causal options. Questions as Probes become tools for measuring and increasing the openness of one’s future histories.
					</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Causal Entropic Forces as telos-inspiration:</strong> The framework borrows the directional intuition and applies it at the level of personal identity. A central design aim is to increase the number and quality of accessible future causal paths while preserving recognizability.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Identity Stem as a causal-influence maximizer:</strong> A strong, coherent Stem with high Mass and well-curved geometry is precisely a system that can exert more influence over its own future. Weak, fragmented, or low-Mass identity reduces future options.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Questions as Probes for entropy measurement:</strong> Precise questions function as instruments to assess how open or closed one’s current identity geometry is with respect to future possibilities — and to deliberately open new paths.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">The most formal scientific anchor:</strong> While all previous anchors are philosophical or psychological, Wissner-Gross supplies a mathematically explicit proposal about intelligence and adaptive behavior. Whether this can ground IE beyond analogy remains open, and IE keeps that uncertainty explicit (see <a href="/critical-gaps" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Critical Gaps</a>).
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Position in the series:</strong> Wissner-Gross is the most formally scientific anchor in this sequence. He connects the ancient philosophical concern with the good life and self-realization to a mathematically stated conjecture about open futures and adaptive behavior. Identity Engineering draws on this as a structuring analogy and long-term aspiration for rigorous grounding — while remaining transparent that the isomorphism is not yet established.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary: Alexander D. Wissner-Gross &amp; Cameron E. Freer, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.110.168702" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">"Causal Entropic Forces," <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Physical Review Letters</em> 110, 168702 (2013)</a>. Note: this is a theoretical proposal in a peer-reviewed physics journal; it is not an established consensus in physics or cognitive science, and has received both interest and critique in the literature.
						</li>
						<li>
							Context and critique: <a href="https://physics.aps.org/articles/v6/46" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">APS Physics focus article (2013)</a> and <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1312.4185" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Kappen, "Comment: Causal entropic forces" (2013)</a>.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						Wissner-Gross is the most formally scientific anchor in the Foundations series. He provides a physics-grounded theoretical proposal that shapes the framework’s central goal: designing identity geometry to keep future causal paths as open as possible. IE draws on this as an analogy and structuring aspiration, not as a derived physical law. The question of whether the analogy can be made rigorous is one of IE’s named open problems.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
